That error is expected — those images no longer exist at that path. Here's what happened and the fix for your setup.

## Why it's failing

Broadcom deleted the public `docker.io/bitnami/*` catalog on **September 29, 2025**. All existing container [Chkk](https://www.chkk.io/blog/bitnami-deprecation) images, including versioned tags like postgresql:13.7.0, were moved to the legacy repository, and the old public catalog was deleted. So `bitnami/postgresql:16` and `bitnami/clickhouse:latest` resolve to nothing. (`:latest` also was never a valid Bitnami tag — they only ever published versioned tags.) The frozen copies now live at `docker.io/bitnamilegacy/*`.

## The fix: don't mirror Bitnami at all

This is exactly why we set every datastore subchart to `deploy: false` in your design. The chart isn't supposed to pull Postgres/ClickHouse — **your own manifests run them, using official multi-arch images** (the Bitnami legacy images aren't reliably arm64, which was the whole reason to avoid them). Mirror these instead:

| You tried (gone) | Mirror this instead | Multi-arch? |
|---|---|---|
| `bitnami/postgresql:16` | `postgres:16` (Docker official) | ✅ arm64 |
| `bitnami/clickhouse:latest` | `clickhouse/clickhouse-server:25.8` | ✅ arm64 |
| `bitnami/valkey` | `valkey/valkey:8` | ✅ arm64 |
| *(minio)* | **not needed** — you use real S3 via IRSA | — |
| *(zookeeper)* | **not needed** — single-node ClickHouse (`clusterEnabled:false`) | — |

Plus `qdrant/qdrant` and the app images `langfuse/langfuse` + `langfuse/langfuse-worker`. Pin each to a current patch tag rather than `latest`.

## Mirror so arm64 is preserved

Critical: a plain `docker pull` on an amd64 machine grabs **only the amd64 layer** — push that to ECR and your pods CrashLoop on Graviton with `exec format error`. Use a manifest-list-aware copy (`crane` or `skopeo`), which copies all architectures:

```bash
aws ecr get-login-password --region <region> \
  | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin <acct>.dkr.ecr.<region>.amazonaws.com
ECR=<acct>.dkr.ecr.<region>.amazonaws.com

crane copy docker.io/library/postgres:16        $ECR/postgres:16
crane copy clickhouse/clickhouse-server:25.8     $ECR/clickhouse-server:25.8
crane copy valkey/valkey:8                        $ECR/valkey:8
crane copy qdrant/qdrant:<pin>                    $ECR/qdrant:<pin>
crane copy langfuse/langfuse:3                     $ECR/langfuse:3
crane copy langfuse/langfuse-worker:3            $ECR/langfuse-worker:3
```

`skopeo copy --all docker://… docker://…` works the same way. (If you must use `docker pull`, add `--platform linux/arm64`.)

Then point the `image:` fields in `apps/langfuse/base/{postgres,clickhouse,valkey}.yaml`, `apps/qdrant/base/statefulset.yaml`, and the `langfuse.web/worker.image.repository` in `values-stg.yaml` at your `$ECR/...` paths.

One thing worth checking: if the Helm release itself is trying to pull `bitnami/postgresql`, then a subchart `deploy:` flag flipped back to `true` somewhere — those should all be `false`. If you did intend to let the chart manage the databases, the only valid source now is `bitnamilegacy/*` with `global.security.allowInsecureImages: true`, but I'd steer you away from that on Graviton since those frozen images aren't guaranteed arm64.

Yes — `bitnami/valkey:latest` "working" is actually its own problem, just a quieter one. It didn't error, but that doesn't mean it's right.

**Why valkey pulled but the other two didn't.** When Broadcom deleted the public `docker.io/bitnami` catalog, they kept a *small community subset* published — but only on the rolling `latest` tag. Valkey happens to be in that subset, so `bitnami/valkey:latest` still resolves. PostgreSQL's *versioned* tags (like `:16`) were all moved out to `bitnamilegacy`, so `bitnami/postgresql:16` is gone. ClickHouse isn't in the free `latest` subset at all, so `bitnami/clickhouse:latest` is gone too. So the three results are all consistent with the same deprecation — valkey just slipped through on the one tag that's left.

**Why you still shouldn't use it:**
1. `:latest` is an unpinned, dev-only, no-longer-updated tag. You don't know what version you're freezing into ECR, and you'll never get a patch. Not something to build staging on.
2. A successful `docker pull` tells you nothing about architecture. Bitnami images aren't guaranteed to ship arm64, and a plain `docker pull && tag && push` grabs **only your machine's arch** (amd64 on most CI) and pushes that single arch to ECR — so on Graviton it'll `exec format error`, or silently run emulated. The pull "succeeding" hid all of that.

**The clean fix is the same for all three — use the official multi-arch images, including valkey:**

```
postgres:16                       (instead of bitnami/postgresql)
clickhouse/clickhouse-server:25.8 (instead of bitnami/clickhouse)
valkey/valkey:8                   (instead of bitnami/valkey:latest)
```

Mirror them with a manifest-list-aware copy so both arches land in ECR:

```bash
crane copy docker.io/library/postgres:16     $ECR/postgres:16
crane copy clickhouse/clickhouse-server:25.8  $ECR/clickhouse-server:25.8
crane copy valkey/valkey:8                     $ECR/valkey:8
```

Then **verify arm64 is actually present** in each ECR image — this is the check that would have caught the valkey issue:

```bash
docker buildx imagetools inspect $ECR/valkey:8
# you should see BOTH linux/amd64 and linux/arm64 listed
```

If you ever do a plain `docker pull`, add `--platform linux/arm64` so you don't mirror amd64 by accident.

